  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and treaties aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some of the most significant ones:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention was one of the first major international efforts to address money laundering. It requires countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** This convention expands the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** This convention focuses on combating corruption and includes provisions related to preventing and combating money laundering related to corruption offenses.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. These standards, known as the FATF Recommendations, are widely recognized and implemented by countries around the world. They cover a wide range of measures, including:\n\n    *   Criminalizing money laundering and terrorist financing\n    *   Customer due diligence requirements for financial institutions\n    *   Reporting suspicious transactions\n    *   International cooperation\n\n*   **Regional Agreements:** In addition to the UN conventions and FATF Recommendations, there are also regional agreements and initiatives aimed at combating money laundering, such as those within the European Union, the Organization of American States, and other regional bodies.\n\nIt's important to note that these international laws and standards require countries to implement domestic laws and regulations to effectively combat money laundering. The specific laws and regulations vary from country to country, but they are generally based on the international standards.",
